 of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dafydd ap Ieuan was born about 1234, in Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Ieuan Blaene ap Philip, was -60 and his mother, Efa ferch Ieuan, was -64. He had at least 3 sons with Mrs. Dafydd ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1234–":"umbes 1234–Surnud","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1238–Female":"1238–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1238":"1238","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","ABT    1262":"umbes 1262","1264":"1264","ABT    1260":"umbes 1260","1296":"1296","1262":"1262","about 1234":"umbes 1234","about 1264":"umbes 1264","1260":"1260","{Rhydderch ap T}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","of,Ystlwyf cmt,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1234–":"noin 1234–Kuollut","1234–Male":"1234–Kuollut","1238–Female":"1238–Kuollut","1260–Male":"126